  "prompt": "Does money laundering fall under criminal legislation?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is considered a criminal offense under criminal legislation in most countries. It involves the process of making illegally obtained money appear legal by passing it through complex financial transactions or legitimate businesses. Many countries have specific anti-money laundering (AML) laws and regulations, and individuals caught engaging in money laundering can face significant criminal penalties, including:\n\n1. Substantial fines\n2. Imprisonment\n3. Asset seizure\n4. Criminal prosecution\n\nThe specific legal framework and penalties vary by jurisdiction, but money laundering is universally treated as a serious criminal activity.",
